The Telegraph - Calcutta : Metro
 Thursday, February 19, 2004  The City Diary
																																																																																		A 25-year-old housewife, Pramila Sardar, and her brother-in-law, Tapas, 19, committed suicide early on Wednesday at Namkhana on the southern fringes of the city by consuming poison. According to superintendent of police, South 24 Parganas, Debkumar Ganguly, the two had an illicit relationship for the past few years and when the whole affair came to light on Tuesday evening, they decided to end their lives. The bodies were recovered from a field adjacent to their house.																																																		The West Bengal Vegetable and Fruit Dealers Association on Wednesday urged state environment minister Manabendra Mukherjee to provide financial assistance for the relocation of the three wholesale vegetable and fruit markets  Koley Market in Sealdah, New Market on Lindsay Street and Tandal Bagan in Howrah  to a sprawling 70 bigha plot near Dhulagarh Truck Terminal in Howrah. Mukherjee welcomed the move and said that the shifting of the markets would decrease the pollution level and ease traffic movement as the trucks bringing in the merchandise would not have to enter the city.																																																		Following a writ petition filed by a television manufacturing-cum-assembling unit, Justice Kalyan Jyoti Sengupta of Calcutta High Court directed the state government to reimburse the sales tax paid by the small-scale unit, or to adjust excess tax paid with payments of the subsequent periods. Small-scale units of different manufacturing categories get reimbursement of the taxed amount, up to the limit of 90 per cent, under the provisions of the West Bengal Industrial Promotion (Assistance to Industrial Units) Scheme 1994.																																																		A middle-aged woman, Kakoli Mahato, of Behala, was arrested on Tuesday night on charges of immoral trafficking. Police said that Mahato was trying to sell off a minor girl when she was caught by local residents and then handed over to the police.																																																		South 24-Parganas police raided several places in Behala on Wednesday and arrested 10 satta bookies. Police said Rs 13,500 and a mobile phone were recovered from them. They have also sealed the premises where the miscreants were caught.																																																		State urban development minister Asok Bhattacharya on Wednesday inaugurated the broadened Garia crossing and the connector to Calcutta Basanti Road along the EM Bypass. Bhattacharya said both CMDA projects, costing Rs 6 crore, were completed on time.																																																		State transport and sports minister Subhas Chakraborty unveiled a swimming pool for children on Wednesday at Beni Banerjee Avenue in Dhakuria. Local MLA Sougata Roy was present on the occasion.To Howrah District Library for launching a drive to collect old manuscripts from households in Howrah for preservation
